{"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "Recipe", "name": "Outcast of the Islands", "description": "Does a cocktail have to include rum in order to be considered a tiki drink? No \u2014 gin will do just fine, too. Jeff Berry created this for Beachbum Berry\u2019s Latitude 29 in New Orleans, and it has become one of its most popular menu items. Ginger liqueur and cinnamon syrup give this gently effervescent number a spicy kick.", "author": {"@type": "Person", "name": "Rosie Schaap"}, "image": "https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/28/magazine/28drink2/28drink3-articleLarge.jpg", "recipeYield": "", "recipeCuisine": "", "recipeCategory": "cocktails", "keywords": "gin, ginger beer, ginger liqueur", "aggregateRating": {"@type": "AggregateRating", "ratingValue": 4, "ratingCount": 5}, "nutrition": {"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "NutritionInformation", "calories": 113, "unsaturatedFatContent": "0 grams", "carbohydrateContent": "11 grams", "cholesterolContent": null, "fatContent": "0 grams", "fiberContent": "0 grams", "proteinContent": "0 grams", "saturatedFatContent": "0 grams", "sodiumContent": "4 milligrams", "sugarContent": "9 grams", "transFatContent": null}, "recipeIngredient": ["1 1/2 oz. London dry gin", "1 oz. fresh lime juice", "1/2 oz. ginger liqueur", "1/2 oz. cinnamon syrup <a href=\"http://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1018010-cinnamon-syrup\">(recipe here)</a>", "1/4 oz. orgeat syrup", "1/8 teaspoon Herbsaint, an anise-flavored liqueur", "1/2 oz. ginger beer"], "recipeInstructions": [{"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "HowToStep", "text": "Shake everything, except ginger beer, with ice. Strain into a cocktail coupe. Pour in ginger beer."}], "link": "https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1018272-outcast-of-the-islands"}